[[File:Ohari-jinja torii.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Torii]]
'''Ohari Shrine''' (おはりじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kita Ward (Okayama)|Q855478|WD=Q855478|lt=Kita Ward|1=Kita-ku, Okayama}}, {{ill|lt=Okayama|Q200078|WD=Q200078|1=Okayama}}, {{ill|lt=Okayama Prefecture|Q132936|WD=Q132936|1=Okayama Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} {{ill|lt=disputed identification shrine|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}, and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
; Principal deity
* '''{{ill|lt=Ame-no-Hoakari-no-Mikoto|Q10940411|WD=Q10940411|1=Amenohoakari}}''' - ancestral deity of the {{ill|lt=Owari clan|Q11465311|WD=Q11465311|1=Owari clan}}

; Associated deity
* {{ill|lt=Ogetsuhime|Q3261482|WD=Q3261482|lt=Ogetsuhime-no-Mikoto|1=Ōgetsuhime}}

Regarding the deity, ''{{ill|lt=Kibi Onko Hiroku|Q11412654|WD=Q11412654|1=Kibi Onko Hiroku}}'' also presents theories identifying it as Otsunane-no-Mikoto or {{ill|lt=Yamato Takeru|Q461258|WD=Q461258|lt=Yamato Takeru-no-Mikoto|1=Yamato Takeru}}<ref name="神々"/>.

=== History ===
The shrine stands on a hill to the east-west side of central Okayama. Behind the shrine buildings remains a group of giant rocks regarded as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=iwasaka|1=UNKNOWN}}, and {{ill|lt=Haji ware|Q5639938|WD=Q5639938|1=Haji pottery}} and {{ill|lt=Sue ware|Q7634351|WD=Q7634351|1=Sue pottery}} have been excavated from the eastern slope<ref name="神々"/>, indicating long-term habitation.

Its founding is unknown, but the area was formerly called "Ifuku-go, Mino District, {{ill|lt=Kibi Province|Q1155128|WD=Q1155128|1=Kingdom of Kibi}}," and is said to have been the settlement of the Ifukube no Muraji (a branch of the {{ill|lt=Owari clan|Q11465311|WD=Q11465311|lt=Owari no Muraji|1=Owari clan}}). The shrine is said to have begun by enshrining their ancestral deity, Ame-no-Hoakari-no-Mikoto<ref>[http://www.okayama-jinjacho.or.jp/cgi-bin/jsearch.cgi?mode=detail&jcode=01091 Ohari Shrine] (Okayama Prefectural Association of Shinto Shrines).</ref>. Nearby stands another shikinaisha connected to the Owari clan, {{ill|lt=Oji Harina Mawakahime Shrine|Q17228003|WD=Q17228003|1=Ojiharina Mawakahime Shrine}}, suggesting a relationship with that clan. There are theories that the Ifukube migrated west from Owari<ref>Recorded in the Meiji-era ''Engishiki Naijinsha / Kokushi Genzai no Jinja'' ("Ohari Shrine" section in ''Nihon no Kamigami'').</ref>, and conversely theories that the Owari clan migrated east from Kibi to Owari<ref>Hiroaki Shimoyama, "Did the ancient Owari clan migrate east from Kibi?" (''Okayama Prefecture Mystery Walk'', Shinjinbutsu Bunko).</ref>.

In the mid-{{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'' lists "Ohari Shrine, Mino District, {{ill|lt=Bizen Province|Q1053688|WD=Q1053688|1=Bizen Province}}" as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and this shrine is considered one of its {{ill|lt=disputed identifications|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}. In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, the exact location of that shikinaisha was said to be unknown<ref name="神々"/>, and some documents of that era state that the shrine land of Sakaori-no-miya (now {{ill|lt=Okayama Shrine|Q11048799|WD=Q11048799|1=Okayama Shrine}}) was the original precinct<ref name="神々"/>. Even now, Ohari Shrine is enshrined among the subordinate shrines of Okayama Shrine, and is regarded as another disputed identification.

Until the early Meiji period it was called "Kurioka-no-miya"<ref name="神々">''Nihon no Kamigami'', section on Ohari Shrine.</ref>. In Meiji it was renamed "Ohari Shrine." Under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, it was ranked a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

